Worlds End Traverse Analysis

Tomas Castillo

June 30, 2016

Exploring Personal Data

Last weekend, I took a trip out to Worlds End State Park in the Northeast part of Pennyslvania. Its nestled in the heart of the Endless Mountains and the Loyalsock State Forest. The route that I picked was not my own choosing, but is in fact a race course for the Worlds End 100k.

I was treating this run as a training experience and a way to explore some of the beautiful and wild parts of the state. And that it was.

I was exploring some other blogs on racing and came across someone who did an analysis on their own training efforts that compared their average paces in each category of grades. I hadnt thought of looking at this approach and decided to pull out my effort at Worlds End to see how my climbing pace looks at different grades.

I tracked the Traverse with a Suunto Ambit3 Peak, and then pulled the data out from Movescount.

This way, the data looks similar to what would show up on Movescount, Strava, TrainingPeaks, MapMyRun, or whatever else might display the GPS data.

If we can explore this to see what weve got, well first just do an overview of what the climbing profile looks like.

Some nice climbs and descents, and all of it was technical! Ha good stuff. I should point out that the race is a 100k category and comes out to 63 miles. Ive got a few excuses for not finishing the full 63 miles, but a majority of the reason was my knees had taken a beating through all the technicality, the heat had taken its toll on my overall strength, and it was getting late and I didnt want to run in the dark since I was alone (I do, in fact, get scared). My total mileage came out to 45 miles. Not bad if you ask me, especially considering the longest I had run before was 36 miles.

Now that weve got that explanation out of the way, lets look a the paces and how the grade of elevation affects it.

First, well just look at the grade of the course.

Something to notice about the data and then to think about in terms of what it means. There are some points over 100%, and even some descents over -200%. Recall that grade is vertical gain/horizontal distance, as a percent (so 1% = 1 ft up for 100 ft horizontal).

Then, if we apply some old fashioned trigonometry, we can figure out the angle. The max grade was 1.27% giving it an angle (in degrees) of 51.7. Thats pretty steep, but actually not unreasonable - its just really steep.

The negative grade of 200% gives us a descent angle of 64. In thinking back, I can probably guess at which point that was because I was going on very slowly and trying to jump from rock to rock as I was descending.

Alright, so well set up some bins that will categorize the grade. The reasoning behind the categories below are what goes from extremely steep, towards a more runnable grade, to flat. Ideally, the grade would be stepped in 2.5% increments, but because of the large range, well lump some of the more extreme grades together.

ggplot(we.traverse, aes(Grade)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.02) +
  coord_trans(y = 'sqrt') +
  scale_y_continuous(minor_breaks = seq(0, 6000, 150),
                     breaks = seq(0, 10000, 2500)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(-2, 150, 0.25),
                     labels = paste0(seq(-2, 150, 0.25)*100, "%")) +
  theme_hc() +
  theme(panel.grid.minor.y = element_line(color = "#d5dbdd", size = 0.5))

As one would expect, most of the grades are actually reasonable and below 50% (both positive and negative). Well add the bins and then plot accordingly.

# Not too many steep grades
gradeBin <- c(-2.5, -1, -0.6, -0.3, -0.25, -0.20, -0.15, -0.125, -0.10, -0.075, -0.05, -0.025, 0,
              0.025, 0.05, 0.075, 0.10, 0.125, 0.15, 0.20, 0.25, 0.3, 0.6, 1, 2.5)

As I was going through this, I realized that we should take out any points that have a speed of 0. The reason for that is its just time that I was still at an aid station (my girlfriends car), resting, or I was navigating trying to find my way back on the trail. Since my watch also records Cadence, we can take out any points I was standing still with a Cadence of 0 as well.

Because were only interested in the metrics related to moving, we can subset the data.

we.traverse <- subset(we.traverse, Speed > 0 & Cadence > 0)
ggplot(we.traverse, aes(x = gradeRank, y = speed.km)) + 
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(width = 1), alpha = 0.2, col = '#b0bcbf') +
  geom_point(stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean, col = '#1b5b83', size =2) +
  scale_x_continuous("Grade Bins",
                     breaks = seq(1, 25,1),
                     labels = paste0(format(gradeBin*100, digits = 0),"%")) +
  scale_y_continuous("Speed [km/h]") +
  theme_hc() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y ~ x*I(x^2)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8,
                                   angle = 90, vjust = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_line(color = "light grey", 
                                          linetype = 2))

While this fit seems to work, I dont usually look at my speed, but rather at my pace. So lets convert Speed to pace. Ive got it in km/h so well need to do a few mathematical transformations first.

we.traverse <- we.traverse %>% 
  mutate(pace = (speed.km*(0.621/60))^(-1))

Well do the same plot as above, but this time, with pace on the y-axis instead of speed.

ggplot(we.traverse, aes(x = gradeRank, y = pace)) + 
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(width = 1, height = 3), alpha = 0.2, col = '#b0bcbf') +
  geom_point(stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean, col = '#1b5b83', size =2) +
  scale_x_continuous("Grade",
                     breaks = seq(1, 25,1),
                   labels = paste0(format(gradeBin*100, digits = 0),"%")) +
  scale_y_continuous("Pace [min/mile]", breaks = seq(0,75,5), 
                     labels = seq(0,75,5), limits = c(0,40)) +
  theme_hc() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y ~ x*I(x^2)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8,
                                   angle = 90, vjust = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_line(color = "light grey", 
                                          linetype = 2))

Good stuff.

So what does a linear model look like for pace over grade? What if we throw in some of the other variables?

Lets start with just pace ~ grade rank.

pg <- lm(pace ~ gradeRank, data = we.traverse)
summary(pg)

Great! While it shows that gradeRank or Grade are both highly correlated thats because its the only variable. We can do better. The low \(R^2\) value doesnt really do much either. So lets look at a few more variables.

Lets back up real quick and evaluate the difference between pace and speed.

While its helpful to think in terms of pace when running, because of the math involved to transform one metric to another, pace has much greater variance depending on how fast/slow Im going.

Recall: \[ pace = (speed[\frac{km}{hr}] * \frac{0.621 miles}{1 km} * \frac{1 hour}{60 min})^{-1} \]

If we look at both of those metrics compared side by side, Speed scales much better for lower and faster speeds. Well stick with using speed instead of pace, and we can transform the variable later when necessary.

In going over these data, I began to think of other ways to categorize things and thought of one that may be helpful, especially in terms of ultras whether Im walking or running. An easy way to pull that out would be to look at the cadence. While this isnt always the case, a good indicator of whether Im running vs walking/hiking is a threshold value in cadence.

Obviously this will vary depending on the person, so Ill have a look at what my values look like.

It would appear that I typically run at between 80-90 spm, while I walk at around 55-60 spm. Note that spm is steps per minute measuring a single leg, not both. A good threshold value would be right at 70.

We can now add a cateogry to our data that tells us whether we are walking or not and then see if that makes sense in terms of speed.

ggplot(we.traverse, aes(x = speed.km, y = Cadence, col = factor(MovementType))) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_hc() +
  scale_color_hc(name = "Movement",
                 breaks = c(0, 1),
                 labels = c("Running", "Walking"))

Hmm, something seems off. Maybe its not as simple as I thought. Even when my cadence was in the walking region, my speed seemed to still indicate I was at running speed. Perhaps, on the downhills, I was taking longer strides?

ggplot(we.traverse, aes(x = Duration/3600, y = Cadence)) +
  geom_point(aes(col = factor(MovementType))) +
  theme_hc() +
  scale_color_hc(name = "Movement",
                 breaks = c(0, 1),
                 labels = c("Running", "Walking")) +
  scale_x_continuous("Duration [Hours]",
                     breaks = seq(0, 12, 1),
                     labels = seq(0, 12, 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Altitude))

All Im gathering from this is there is no easy distinction to determine whether Im walking or not. Because of that, we will remove the categorical variable for MovementType. It might be easier to extract than I realize, but for now well remove that category and can explore it later.

It may take a little to look through the different models, but were just comparing the different variables and theyre output effect.

Something else that may be quite helpful is the duration to which the event has taken. For example, look at the gradeRank vs Pace graph, and around the 0% - 2.5% grade region, there are some high points, but also some low points that are in the walking range (lower).

2.5% is a pretty mild grade. However, depending on the time of day and how my legs were feeling, I may have decided to walk even a small hill instead. It may not always be an influencing factor, but I think it may shed some additional light on the entire picture.

Lets add duration to our model.
